00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:36.620
&gt;&gt; Abdullah Ibrahim: Yeah.

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:38.630
&gt;&gt; Dan Morgenstern: And
I found their review

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:45.380
from Down Beat way back, and let's
see, Junior Booth was the bassist.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:49.220
&gt;&gt; Abdullah Ibrahim:
Junior Booth, yeah.

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:54.160
He just, he just arrived in New
York shortly He was from Buffalo.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.530
Great bass player.

00:02:55.530 --> 00:03:01.470
Alright. You know, I remember that,
and then I went on to form a trio

00:03:01.470 --> 00:03:07.010
with the Bad Lancaster and
Kello Scott [assumed spelling],

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:08.310
the cellist.

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:13.620
&gt;&gt; Dan Morgenstern: Oh, Kello Oh,
he was a wonderful player, yeah.

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:17.680
Yeah, he just made a handful
of records, not enough.

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:20.790
And people don't know
about him anymore, no.

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:22.090
&gt;&gt; Abdullah Ibrahim: No.

00:03:22.090 --> 00:03:25.020 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Dan Morgenstern: And that was
such an unusual instrument and, and.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:30.510
&gt;&gt; Abdullah Ibrahim: Of course, you
know, cello, and I was interested

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:32.750
in playing cello since I was a kid.

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:36.880
When I got to New York, I got a
little cello and started playing.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:44.280
But then, I met Kello, and Kello
also introduced us to kodaly.

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:50.200
And of course, kodaly cello
suites, really resonates with,

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:53.530
also with our dynamic
of our understanding,

00:03:53.530 --> 00:04:00.770
how can we expand the harmonic
and rhythmic possibilities.

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:06.160
So I formed a trio with Bad
Lancaster on bass clarinet,

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:11.650
and Kello on cello,
and myself on piano.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:16.900
And then I went to a New York
club, I can't remember where he was

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:20.370
and I said, would you like
to book me, I've got a trio?

00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:22.970
They said fine, but when we
pieced off the other night,

00:04:22.970 --> 00:04:27.720
they didn't want to play me,
because that's not a trio.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:30.050
You see a trio is bass,
drums [laughter].

00:04:30.050 --> 00:04:40.050
So it took me 50, 60
years to create it again,

00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:43.230
and that was the unit
that we saw last night.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:44.530
&gt;&gt; Dan Morgenstern: Yes.

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:47.560
&gt;&gt; Abdullah Ibrahim:
This was the idea.

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:50.510
&gt;&gt; Dan Morgenstern: That was a,
